From b1ddfb0b9ce2048e834b1bbf1b49b1e22db69791 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ahmed Wafdy <ahmedadelwafdy782@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 1 Mar 2026 00:42:17 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] =?UTF-8?q?TEGRA234=20WORKAROUND:=20Clear=20any=20stale=20?=
 =?UTF-8?q?CCPMU=20RAS=20error=20left=20by=20MB2=20firmware=20before=20doi?=
 =?UTF-8?q?ng=20ANYTHING=20else=20=E2=80=94=20in=20particular=20before=20t?=
 =?UTF-8?q?he=20first=20MCE=20ARI=20call.?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

MB2 writes a poison address (0x60a5a5a5a5a5a5a5) into CCPMU ERR0ADDR to detect uninitialised-memory accesses.  It leaves ERR0STATUS.V=1 on exit.  Under a normal UEFI boot the UEFI ExitBootServices callback clears this before handing control to the OS.  When Xen is the bootloader it bypasses ExitBootServices, so the stale error survives into BL31.  Once SCR_EL3.EA=1 is set any pending SError is routed to EL3, fires during the ERET to the non-secure world, and either:
(a) hits assert(selected!=NULL) in tegra234_ras_handler because the SDEI dispatch table is not yet populated, or
(b) causes the MCE ARI mailbox to wedge, producing "ARI request timed out" for every subsequent ARI call.

I mirror the live ERR0STATUS bits into the W1C write so that we clear exactly the fields that are set, without touching reserved bits.

Another Tegra234 workaround: mask CCPMU RAS interrupt sources at the IH before ERET to non-secure world.

Adding the kill + idle-wait sequence gives the MCE FW what it needs to resume normal operation before ATF tries ari_online_core() for secondary CPUs.

When a previous ARI command leaves an error code in ARI_STATUS, the next call sees those bits set and the pre-flight poll correctly identifies the mailbox as busy — but nothing ever clears ARI_STATUS between commands.
The T234 ARI spec says ARI_STATUS is cleared by the MCE firmware when it accepts a new request — but only if the previous request was cleanly completed. If it ended in an error state, the MCE FW expects SW to issue a KILL before accepting the next request.

- add per-core IH masking for the secondary CPU
tegra234_ras_init_my_cluster calls ih_write_ras_general_enb
which re-enables the IH interrupt sources after bl31_plat_runtime_setup
masked them — undoing the mask for each secondary CPU.

Fix: Increase ARI_MAX_RETRY_COUNT for ONLINE_CORE only
The existing ARI_MAX_RETRY_COUNT of 2,000,000 was designed for fast ARI commands (cache clean, cstate update) that complete in microseconds. ONLINE_CORE for first-cluster bring-up needs a much larger budget.

first-cluster bring-up requires DSU-AE L3 ECC scrub (2MiB) which takes significantly longer than a normal ARI command at cold-boot clock frequencies.
